CHOLERA, DIARRHEA AND DYSENTERY UPDATE (47): HAITI
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 12 Sep 2013
Source: Andina [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://www.andina.com.pe/Espanol/noticia-mas-300-muertos-por-colera-haiti-desde-enero-474173.aspx#.UjM0rNK-2So


At least 312 people have died so far in 2013 as a result of the cholera epidemic that continues to affect Haiti, which has accounted for more than 35 000 since January 2013, according to a new balance sheet from the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs.

Despite the fact that cholera has continued to cause deaths in an almost uninterrupted manner since the earthquake in January 2010, the medical centers that serve specifically the epidemic were reduced.

The latest report of the United Nations in the Caribbean country, picked up by the local news portal Alter Presse, the number of cholera centers has fallen by 16 percent between 2012 and 2013. Also, the UN warned that the medical facilities that are still active have fewer external support -- 30 percent less -- and lack sufficient funding.

The worsening healthcare has resulted in an increase in the mortality rate, which reached maximum rates in some areas between June and August 2013. The hurricane season still active for 3 more months, also threatens the population.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The epidemic of cholera in Haiti continues, fed by a totally inadequate sanitary system and decreasing external financial support. The tropical storm/hurricane season, which lasts until November, will add an exclamation point to the number of cases.

The Haitian epidemic spread to the Dominican Republic that shares the island with Haiti and also to Cuba. These countries have had cholera cases exported to other countries in the Americas and Europe. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/22DW.]
